humanrace Samba Colors by pharrell   The elevated iteration of our Iconic Samba silhouette is a celebration of craftsmanship high-quality materials and colorways that embody the diversity of Humanrace’s DNA.   Made with all-around premium leather upper leather lining and leather shoelaces from ECCO Leather. The raw materials are transformed into the adidas Samba Leather through eccoleather’s water-saving tanning technology which saves 20 liters of water per hide resulting in higher color fastness and better performance. The extended tongue is a nod to the Samba’s rich football heritage.  Now available on humanrace.com and CONFIRMED – hit the link in bio to shop. #adidasPharrellWilliams

A First Look At A First…M0.0NSHOT – the world’s first net zero carbon shoe – is the culmination of years of work to reduce carbon across our business and products since day one. The landmark 0.0 kg CO₂e carbon footprint (versus a standard sneaker which is about 14 kg CO2e based on our calculations) will be achieved without relying on a single carbon offset. Excited? It’s Earth Day. And we’re going green(washing). Not really but… Did we get your attention?We know that when it comes to corporate sustainability commitments it’s hard to know what’s real. The threat of greenwashing–false or misleading statements about the environmental benefits of products or services–leaves people feeling rightfully skeptical especially on days like Earth Day.To shed light on the issue we’re launching the Earth Day Greenwashed Collection. Available only on our resale marketplace ReRun this special assortment of pre-loved green styles is the only kind of greenwashing we’re into. Because when Earth Day is over and this collection is long gone our work to lower our environmental impact is here to stay. And we’re committed to sharing our progress along the way so you don’t have to sort sustainability fact from fiction.Learn more about the collection and our everyday commitments at the link in bio.

Did you know our Tree Collection of shoes is made with wood-based fibers? 👟 For real. It’s called TENCEL™ Lyocell and it’s produced by our friends at Lenzing. This wonder material is made in a closed-loop process resulting in close-to-zero waste. Plus TENCEL™ Lyocell fibers are made with at least 50% less carbon emissions and water consumption than similar fabrics. All that math adds up to doing less harm to the planet—and keeps us rooted in responsibility. 🌳

The Day Glove⁣⁣A shoe that fits like a glove—and hustles all damn day.⁣⁣The Day Glove is made of buttery soft leather that molds to your foot for ⁣a perfect custom fit. Since it’s 2018 debut it quickly became a customer-favorite selling over 300k pairs and counting. Named for its all-day ⁣wearability this luxurious style is a stalwart to any forever wardrobe. ⁣⁣Offered in a variety of complementary colors with features like a back ⁣pull tab side vents a rubber sole and a cushioned insole it is the ⁣ultimate shoe to marry comfort and style.⁣⁣This season we are happy to introduce Comfort Fit an updated fit to these best-sellers that caters to a wider range of foot widths. In addition to ⁣ensuring a consistent fit across the rest of our Day Family there’s no longer any guesswork when it comes to sizing. The foot beds are also now ⁣dyed to match the color of the shoe resulting in a more elevated finish. ⁣⁣Day to day. Day to night. Days to come. ⁣⁣#Everlane #LeatherFlats #TheLeatherDayGlove

Empowered strong and sexy. Thats what I hope people feel when they wear anything I make. Martine Rose details the emotional undercurrent of her latest Nike collaboration. 2023: The Year in StyleFashion’s game of musical chairs resumed with a steady beat in 2023. Peter Do announced his arrival at Helmut Lang with a subtle remix of the house’s signature codes while Seán McGirr took over for Sarah Burton at Alexander McQueen. Among the most highly anticipated appointments in years Pharrell Williams took the reins at Louis Vuitton as Daniel Lee looked to the past to bring Burberry into a new era.Actors Greta Lee and Ayo Edebiri cut through the noise with breakout roles in ‘Past Lives’ and ‘The Bear’ respectively while Fred Again and Ice Spice established themselves as dominant musical forces. Their individual successes set them up to become contemporary muses in 2024 and beyond.The year was also marked by the loss of figures who shaped contemporary culture. Designer Paco Rabanne and original It girl Jane Birkin left behind legacies that span decades. Angus Cloud continues to influence and inspire through the art that echoes in his wake. The unparalleled impact of Born x Raised co-founder Spanto lives on in his hometown of Los Angeles and in streetwear communities around the world.Discover our End of Year roundup only on GOAT.com/editorial

2023: The Year in SneakersFrom Air Jordan to adidas brands balanced aesthetics and technology to engineer designs that dictated the pace of the year’s footwear dialogue.Loewe and Jacquemus worked with ON and Nike respectively to create luxury sneakers that resonated with both lifestyle and performance audiences while Corteiz and Sandy Liang updated Nike’s Air Max 95 and Salomon’s XT-6 with details that added to each silhouette’s place in the wider conversation. MSCHF’s Big Red Boot took the oversized sneaker concept to the extreme creating a silhouette that was more wearable art than practical footwear.One design towered above the rest however. Blending the worlds of skateboarding and basketball no sneaker topped the cultural impact of the Nike SB x AJ4 Retro ‘Pine Green.’ With a fully leather construction streamlined forefoot and gum sole this reimagining of an icon was proof that perfection can indeed be improved upon.Discover our End of Year roundup only on GOAT.com/editorial

The Metropolitan Museum of Art celebrates the life and work of Karl Lagerfeld with the Met Gala 2023. One of the most prolific designers of the past century Lagerfeld modernized the codes of luxury transforming Chanel Fendi and his eponymous brand into cultural phenomenons.Throughout his career the German visionary cultivated creative relationships with fashion icons—including Kate Moss Devon Aoki and Naomi Campbell—to debut his artistic vocabulary in elaborately staged runway shows. His influence continues to inform the direction of style today visible in the form of designs that blur the lines between playfulness and provocation.Explore the legacy of Karl Lagerfeld only on the app and GOAT.com

2023: The Year in StyleFollowing season after season of spectacle runway shows felt more sincere this year. Nigerian-born London-based designer Mowalola enlisted a multidisciplinary crew of rising creatives in London while Coperni echoed the unforgettable drama of Alexander McQueen’s 1999 ‘Savage Beauty’ show with the addition of robotic dogs in Milan.Miuccia Prada’s Miu Miu merged the corporate world with Y2K codes joining a series of microtrends that encompassed an emo renaissance driven by nostalgia for a pre-internet era and a soccer-inflected blokecore movement. As a sharp counterpoint to logomania luxury fashion went into stealth mode swapping bold wordmarks for ultra-fine materials and expert craftsmanship.Explore our End of Year roundup only on GOAT.com/editorial

2023: The Year in SneakersFrom the New Balance 550 to the Nike Dunk this year proved iconic silhouettes have no expiration date.Bella Hadid sparked a frenzy around the Onitsuka Tiger Mexico 66—first released in 1966—while Wales Bonner helped adidas introduce the nearly 75-year-old Samba to a new generation. Simultaneously Aminé and Action Bronson’s New Balance treatments helped transform wardrobe staples into unexpected standouts.Sneaker brands looked towards nature for inspiration replacing barbiecore pink with bold shades of green. Beyond the color spectrum performance-oriented silhouettes from Hoka One One Salomon and ON ensured that form and functionality remained a dominant factor in the evolving world of footwear.Explore our End of Year roundup only on GOAT.com/editorial

1994 to 2016 to present.Consuelo Castiglioni founded MARNI in 1994 in Milan Italy bringing a wide range of colorful fabrics to the world of luxury. Francesco Risso joined the house in 2016 introducing a sense of surrealism to the brand’s signature use of bold prints and patterns. Risso continues to expand the reaches of MARNI’s kaleidoscopic universe today applying eccentric color stories to select knitwear—now considered iconic in the pantheon of contemporary fashion.Discover era-defining styles curated for Style Catalog FW23 only on the app and GOAT.com

Iconic style. Unbound by time.Karl Lagerfeld experimented with CHANEL motifs throughout the 2000s honoring and subverting brand codes in seasonal collections. Accessories played a pivotal role in reinventing the maison for the new millennium often expressed in the form of organic shapes and metallic colors.HELMUT LANG founded his eponymous label in 1986. The Austrian designer pioneered minimalism in the ’90s through angular tailoring and utilitarian garments adorned with straps and harnesses. Tinker Hatfield designed the Air Jordan 12 for Michael Jordan’s fifth championship season. Bringing back the iconic ‘Cherry’ colorway for 2023 the silhouette features radial stitching across the white leather upper inspired by the sunbeams on Japan’s Rising Sun flag. Experimental designer and GREATEST alum Nicole McLaughlin brings her sustainability-minded approach to Hoka’s Mafate Three2. 2001. 2009.Following a one-year sabbatical RAF SIMONS returned to the runway for FW01 with ‘Riot! Riot! Riot!’ The collection rejected the slim silhouettes of Simons’ previous work instead focusing on hyper-stylized representations of youth angst. Emerging as an early highlight of the collection the oversized bomber jacket signaled a turning point in fashion’s relationship with subcultures marking an early instance of streetwear’s ethos infiltrating the rarefied world of luxury.Equally influential MAISON MARGIELA unveiled a parachute cargo vest for SS09. Constructing the silhouette out of 10 pockets—each in a different material and pattern—the piece demonstrated the house’s conceptual roots. Pushing the experimental narrative further each zipper was rendered in a different color embodying Margiela’s heritage of couture artisanship.Explore era-defining styles curated for Style Catalog FW23 only on the app and GOAT.com

“Chrome Hearts has nothing to do with the fashion world. We don’t have any seasons. Design revolutions are built on the groundbreaking ideas of creative visionaries and the stories they tell through their work. Radical Design celebrates this concept with a selection of pieces from influential voices showcasing the objects that revealed new ways of seeing.The exhibition brings together over 70 items across disciplines from Memphis Milano tables and Alessi kitchenware to Issey Miyake apparel and Raf Simons footwear. Rare archival discoveries are offered exclusively via auction including sample pairs of Marc Newson’s modular space-age sneakers for Nike and Maison Margiela’s first-ever sunglasses from SS08.Presented in partnership with capsule.global Radical Design is the first of an ongoing series of Exhibits hosted on GOAT. Each edition examines a creative movement from design and fashion to sports and music.Explore Radical Design now only on the GOAT app and GOAT.com

“I am always learning always discovering.” - Isamu NoguchiThe Japanese-American architect designer and artist helped define midcentury aesthetics with the debut of his Akari light sculptures in 1951. #GANNIHELLOWORLD #SS24“Nicolaj has a background in tech so we have been talking about Artificial Intelligence for years. Recently it feels like something else to panic about because it’s so far from my world. But I was thinking about AI’s potential for good. As a mother of three kids and as a woman running a business I think a lot about how to raise my kids to be kind to feel secure to be responsible. It’s the same with GANNI how do we grow this brand into the most responsible business it can be? So we talked about how it might be possible to create a kinder more thoughtful AI one that does good. Everything clicked into place when we met the incredible AI artist Cecilie Waagner Falkenstrøm who has this thoughtful philosophical take on AI. We worked with Cecilie to create a GANNI AI for the show. We wanted the spirit of the AI to be embodied by a physical form something natural - my first thought was trees – they are such a symbol of hope and life. Internally our team is unbelievably strong premier league. And the wider GANNI community is… it’s everything.” – Ditte Reffstrup Creative Director GANNI#CPHFWGANNI Creative direction: ditte_reffstrup Concept and art direction: moon_intl Styling: emelierjohansson Hair:  cimmahony studiocimmahony Make-up: trineskjoeth products by theordinary Choreography: mariannehaugli Casting director: aamo_casting Production: thelabcph Location ciffdkGANNI AI: ceciliefalkenstrom artificialmind_ai Trees: sitasplanteskoleMusic: mobilegirl Photography: nordgrenmathiasDirector of Photography: petervintergaard

THE FUTURE OF FABRICS IS COMING GANNI ‘Fabrics of The Future’ initiative was set up to research develop and invest in pioneering startups and innovative materials that are alternatives to virgin materials. Innovative materials like Celium™ by Polybion grown by nurturing bacteria with fruit waste Savian by BioFluff a plant-based fur alternative and bio-based Oleatex produced using waste streams from olive oil production helps fashion become more circular and to get us closer to our goal of a 50% absolute carbon reduction by 2027.Stay tuned to discover more in our FUTURE TALENT FABRICS exhibition next week & find out more at ganni.lab

GANNI GUIDE TO COPENHAGEN SS24 EDITIONFor our SS24 HELLO WORLD show we’re exploring the intersection between the digital and natural world. We’ve created a GANNI Guide to our favourite summer spots in CPH that encourage you to get you outside and be with nature come rain or shine 🌥️.aurensdeli  keeps local produce at the heart of their deli growing vegetables on their own local farm plot to serve in storearkenmuseum Nature Dreams 2023 - an exhibition ft. tech art by Refik Anadol where large data sets and algorithms are used to create abstract ai-generated images of nature all ceaselessly changing and existing only in a machine. labanchina here you will only find farm-to-table locally-sourced food. Expect no meat only fish together with great coffee snacks and organic biodynamic wines and take a dip in the water while you’re there.J.C. Jacobsen’s Garden is the perfect spot for tree spotting some of the trees here date from when the garden was laid out in 1849.grospiseri is the very first Danish rooftop farm + restaurant serving up breakfast and dinner in the centre of Copenhagen – using their own harvested produce  ostergro - the vision of ØsterGro is to provide local and fresh vegetables honey and eggs to people in the city. Every Tuesday during the season volunteers are welcomed to help on the rooftop farm.#GANNIHELLOWORLD#SS24 #CPHFW

HOW WE DECORATE FOR THE HOLIDAY SEASON 🎀WITH RESPONSIBILITY IN MINDBows are taking centre stage this season at GANNI when it comes to our Pre Spring 2024 collection and are the symbol of this year’s holiday season campaign. So of course we had to decorate our office top-to-toe in bows - made from iconic GANNI leftover fabrics from years gone by.Responsibility is at the core of everything we do which is why we love making smaller responsible efforts in our offices - even when it comes down to how we decorate for the holiday season.What we do at our GANNI offices won’t single-handedly save the planet but it’s a small reminder for us all to make more responsible choices every day no matter how small for ourselves GANNI and the planet.What’s your best tip to decorate more responsibly for the holiday season? #GANNILAB

GANNI x 66north Adventure awaitsInspired by a mutual love of Iceland and the great outdoors our fourth collab is designed to support energetic adventurous lifestyles.Bringing together playfulness with practicality this collab fuses together Scandi 2.0 with the heritage Icelandic labels tradition of crafting extreme weather gear since 1926. Designing a collection from two B-Corp certified brands that features a mix of recycled materials 80% certified post-consumer recycled down and high-performance technological fabrics including recycled GORE-TEX WINDSTOPPER®.Water-resistant windproof and breathable - #GANNIX66NORTH lets you revel in the worlds natural beauty while remaining protected against the elements.

SPRING SUMMER 2024 #GANNILAB HIGHLIGHTS <3Runway photos by Mathias NordgreenSS24 celebrates transformation change and positivity - this is our first collection without any virgin leather across both accessories and ready-to-wear. For SS24 we’ve furthered our Fabrics Of The Future efforts by working with 3 innovative textile start-ups: oleatex -  a plant-based olive leather alternative made from waste streams from olive oil production. algreen_technology - plastic-free bio-sequins made from seaweed and agricultural waste that can be recycled. circulose® by Renewcell - a new natural material made via textile waste and Circulose® which transforms textile waste into a new material without the need for cotton fields oil or trees.Fabric innovations need to play a crucial role in making fashion more circular but for that to happen we need to place bets take risks and raise awareness. We need to push these innovations on our runways to promote them and over time create commercially scaleable businesses -  which is why you will see us introduce plastic-free and recyclable sequins by algreen_technology on a runway showpiece - set to be commercilly ready in 2025.Our Fabrics of The Future initiative helps us get closer to our goal of a 50% absolute carbon reduction by 2027. By 2025 we aim to have 10% of our materials from innovative Fabrics of The Future. #GANNILAB #GANNIHELLOWORLD

OLIVE YOU 🫒oleatex is a next-generation material featuring a biobased element known as “Biotex” derived from olive oil production waste in Turkey. This process sees the olive oil production waste being turned into a biopolymer resulting in a triple-layered material with a bio-based PU  top coating that is backed with cotton and viscose. Composition: 65% PU 23% Recycled Polyester 7% Cotton 5% Viscose.Oleatex is part of our Fabric of the Future initiative set up to research develop and scale innovative materials that are paving the way for the future of fashion.

As you may have seen during our ‘FUTURE TALENT’ FABRICS’ exhibition at CPHFW this January we’ve been working closely with innovation partners to introduce next-gen leather alternative GANNI Bou Bags as part of our Fabrics of the Future initiative.Materials like Celium by Polybion (bacteria grown leather alternatives) Savian by BioFluff (a plant-based fur alternative) and Oleatex ( a leather alternative based on olive oil production waste) are paving the way for the future of fashion and are on our roadmap. We are still in the process of scaling some of these Fabrics Of The Future materials but have already launched the GANNI Bou bag in Ohoskin last year pictured here in black! Ohoskin is a bio-based material and luxury leather alternative made from waste streams of orange and cactus farming and recycled plastic.Each of the Ohoskin BOU bags has a composition consisting of 45% bio-attributed PVC with orange and cactus-based biopolymer 40% green plasticizers 15% Recycled polyester.**Disclaimer: The EU Fibre regulation allows only a selection of named and approved materials to be declared on the product/label. For legal reasons the trademarked names for these Fabric innovations are not (yet) registered as a known fibre or input. This is what’s known as a ‘next-generation material’ and is therefore labelled in the composition differently.

Introducing GRADIENTS by laurastarup 💗🩵Discover our bespoke art piece installation at our GANNI HQ in Copenhagen crafted from leftover iconic GANNI fabrics created by emerging textile artist and designer (+ Team GANNI alumni) laurastarup.Walking the stairs at our GANNI HQ in Copenhagen you are taken on a nostalgic tour of iconic prints and fabrics from GANNI seasons gone by going from blue shades to pink. Doing what we do best we have surrounded ourselves with amazing talent from near and far growing new friendships and collaborations. In 2020 we launched our creative collective as a further exploration of creative energy drawing on different perspectives and emerging designers from around the world. It’s a way to collaborate and create in fresh new ways doing something totally different with responsibility in mind.While we are fully aware that what we do or decorate our GANNI offices with won’t single-handedly save the planet it’s a small reminder for us all to make more responsible choices every day no matter how small for ourselves GANNI and the planet.Swipe through to get to know more about Laura Starup and her thoughts behind the artpiece and how she hopes that emerging designers and art can help push forward reflections and actions towards positive change.📸 bettykrag

DESIGNER SPOTLIGHT: Sisse Bjerre GANNI Next-Gen Talentsissebjerre is redefining and challenging traditional hand-craftsmanship and industrial creative processes. The Swedish School of Textiles graduate explores alternative processes of making garments using paper as a primary medium and experimenting with natural materials including moss and branches to convey a visual narrative between fantasy and reality.GANNI FUTURE TALENT FABRICS Exhibition: Sisse has created a piece titled ‘Paper Land’ using circulose combined with paper-mâché and paper collage techniques.sissebjerre with muse amanda.elenaPhotographed by bettykrag

HOW TO CLOTHE 10 BILLION PEOPLE SUSTAINABLYA massive question with no easy answers.Yesterday GANNI Founder Nicolaj Reffstrup took part as speaker on the panel ‘How to Clothe 10 Billion People Sustainably’ at COP28 at the UN Climate Change Conference in Dubai. The panel was moderated by iammuchaneta alongside panelists representing global voices in the fashion industry. Addressing these like human rights textile waste recycling initiatives consumer awareness and activism as a way to drive change in the fashion industry and challenges in large-scale production settings.As Fashion is one of the biggest carbon culprits do you think they should have a seat at the table to solve the issues at hand?Slide to read key highlights and watch the full conversation via link in bio.#COP28 #UNclimatechange #UNFCCC#GANNILAB

DESIGNER SPOTLIGHT: Sarah Brunnhuber GANNI Next-Gen Talentsarah_brunn is a textile designer and the founder of stem______ . Stem strives towards true renewal within the fashion industry offering an industry-changing approach to how clothing is produced – eliminating garment production waste and creating a visual aesthetic that tells a production story. Stem’s philosophy is: Produce better produce less – buy better buy less.GANNI FUTURE TALENT FABRICS Exhibition: Sarah has created her pieces titled ‘Stem Elastic 100% Wool Handwoven Edition’ using her own leftover yarns developed with Berlin-based yarn research studio HILO to produce something new using innovative zero-waste weaving techniques.stem______ with muse veronicadsouzaPhotographed by bettykrag

ganni.lab here to talk to you about bio_fluff our newest Fabric of the Future. BioFluff is the first-ever 100% plant-based faux fur made using natural plant fibres and zero petrochemicals. For this years Global Fashion Agenda globalfashionagenda well be showcasing existing Fabrics of The Future we have worked with in collections and introduced as well as an exclusive fluffy jacket made in partnership with next-gen Danish designer nicklasskovgaard – made entirely from animal-friendly BioFluff. Unlike most faux-fur alternatives it has zero plastic so theres no nasty micro-plastic shedding but its still as cuddly + cosy. Slide through the exclusive pieces and read more on why we’ve got a soft spot for bio_fluff.Copenhagen family learn more about our Fabrics of The Future initiative + see the exclusive pieces at our pop-up.GANNI Bremerholm June 27th - July 1st#GANNILAB

DESIGNER SPOTLIGHT: A. ROEGE HOVE cphfw NEWTALENT AlumniCopenhagen knitwear brand a.roegehove pushes the boundaries of material behaviour challenging long-held traditions and perceptions. Founded by Amalie Røge Hove the brand first began with a line of knitted bags which immediately became a hit with Copenhagen’s fashion elite and has since expanded into clothing ranging from fluid to sculptural pieces each celebrating the female form.GANNI FUTURE TALENT FABRICS Exhibition: Amalie has created her piece titled ‘ARH look 01’ using Fabrics of The Future InResST™ Recycled Nylon circulose and post-consumer recycled wool yarn from Omega yarn mill combined with her own leftover yarns.Muse mmminkim photographed by bettykrag

DESIGNER SPOTLIGHT: Nicklas Skovgaard cphfw NEWTALENT GraduateDanish designer nicklasskovgaard explores the relationship textiles can hold in expressing a narrative through unexpected material and classical form. Each of his designs weaves together a spectrum of inspirations.GANNI FUTURE TALENT FABRICS Exhibition: Nicklas has created a full look featuring ‘The Lecia Coat’ with leggings & hat using Fabrics of The Future savian.bio oleatex and circulose .Muse annaravnlei photographed by bettykrag

DESIGNER SPOTLIGHT: Sahar Jamili GANNI Next-Gen TalentHolding a BFA from the Royal Academy of Fine Arts Sahar Jamili is a Danish-Azerbaijani-Iranian visual artist. Having grown up in Copenhagen their work aims to confront racism within Denmark and pays tribute to those surviving it. Sahar’s process is deeply rooted in storytelling drawing inspiration from their own lived experiences.GANNI FUTURE TALENT FABRICS Exhibition: Sahar has created a sculpture piece titled ‘Trapped 2024 Aluminium Unsaleable GANNI clothes’ featuring an aluminium cage filled with GANNI textile waste that is usually sent to I:CO our recycling partner – presenting a visual commentary on overconsumption within the fashion industry.me_unit Photographed by bettykrag
What rhymes with Bou? 💘
Head to toe summer 🌇 #GANNI

DESIGNER SPOTLIGHT: Jens Ole Árnason GANNI Next-Gen TalentCopenhagen-based designer and textile artist jensolearnason has a BA and MA in Fashion Design from Design School Kolding. By building on his knowledge from his fashion background Jens Ole challenges traditional textile craftsmanship presenting new ways of textile creation and manipulation through not only fashion but also sculpture wall art and installations.GANNI FUTURE TALENT FABRICS Exhibition: Jens Ole has created a sculptural art piece called ‘GreenFutureXSculpture’ using GANNI leftover fabrics that have been embroidered and glazed with oil.‘GreenFutureXSculpture’ by jensolearnason Photographed by bettykrag

DESIGNER SPOTLIGHT: Alectra Rothschild / MASCULINA cphfw NEWTALENT Ones To WatchMaking waves with subversive collections celebrating queer and counterculture Copenhagen-based designer alectrarothschild has built clothing brand iwantmasculina on the notions of expression and high-glamour. Her body-conscious clothes either hug or control the body for a dramatic undressed and slightly chaotic aesthetic.GANNI FUTURE TALENT FABRICS Exhibition: Alectra has created two pieces titled ‘A Phone Call With Trixie’ featuring a corset and shredded denim trousers using Fabrics of The Future oleatex and circulose .Muse proxy__server photographed by bettykrag

Introducing the launch of our exciting new adaptive collection. This adaptive underwear collection is specifically designed with accessibility in mind to empower disabled people and those living with health conditions or impairments.The first four pieces an adaptive lingerie capsule are part of our growing product range in this space. With the innovatively designed pieces starting from £8/€10/€10NE/Kč260 in sizes ranging from 2XS to 2XL we’re proud to bring affordable adaptive products to the high street 🖤 #PrimarkVideo Description: Three models highlight the features of our new adaptive lingerie collection while sharing their personal perspectives about the range. Dressed in black lingerie they demonstrate the functionality of the closures on the front of the bra and the sides of the briefs. They are filmed individually and collectively seated and standing together in a studio engaged in conversation and sharing laughter. Emma a white woman with blonde wavy mid-length hair is using a red electric wheelchair. Glen a black woman with long brown braids wears artificial limbs on both legs and has a limb difference on her left hand. Tegan a black woman with mid-length dark brown curly hair has Cerebral Palsy.

Make Primark sugar cookies with jemmaloi 💙❄️ #Primark⬇️What you’ll need 🍪:350g plain flour100g self-raising flour130g softened cubed butter130g golden syrup130g granulated sugar1 tsp vanilla extract1 egg beaten450g Royal Icing Sugar75ml waterFood colouringHow to 🧑‍🍳:Cookies•	Combine both flours and sugar in a large mixing bowl then add the cubed butter. Rub together between your fingers until it resembles a sand like consistency. •	Make a well in the centre and add the egg golden syrup and vanilla extract. Mix to combine and then bring together into two small dough balls. Lay each ball of dough between two sheets of greaseproof paper and roll to about 0.5mm thick. Chill in the fridge for 30-60 minutes. •	Pre heat your oven to 170°c and line two trays with greaseproof paper. Remove the dough from the fridge and cut out your cookie shapes laying them on the trays. Bake for 8-10 minutes and allow to cool completely before decorating. Icing: •	Combine both ingredients in a mixing bowl and beat at a medium-high speed until the consistency resembles toothpaste. Use as many small bowls as you need colours and add food colouring to each one until you have your desired shade. Add half of each colour to piping bags and put to one side. These are for the outlines. With the remaining icing colours add little amounts of water until you have a thinner consistency to ‘flood’ in between your outlines. Put these in piping bags too.  •	To ice your biscuits snip a tiny hole at the end of your piping bags and begin by creating an outline with your thicker icing you will then use the flood icing to colour in your outlines. •	Leave to dry overnight or in a low oven for 30 minutes.

Home-made roasted nuts 🥜 #Primark #DIY ⬇️ What you need for Roasted Nuts🌰: 400g grams of plain mixed nuts.1 tbsp of butter40ml water75g caster sugar1 tsp sweet paprika½ tsp ground black pepper1 tsp fine salt How to 🧑‍🍳: •  Pre heat the oven to 180c and line a large tray with greaseproof paper.•  Add the nuts to medium sized bowl and add the black pepper sweet paprika salt and stir to combine.•  Heat the butter sugar and water in a small pan until the sugar has just dissolved (1-2 minutes on a medium heat)•  Pour over your nuts and stir well ensuring they are evenly coated.•  Spread out on the baking tray and roast in the oven for 15 minutes stirring halfway through.•  Allow to cool slightly before handling. What you need for Cheesy Puff Stars 🧀: •  1 roll of ready-made puff pastry.•  50g grated cheddar cheese mixed with 15g parmesan.•  2-3 tbsp milk•  Seasoning of your choice How to 🧑‍🍳: •  Pre heat the oven to 180c and line two baking trays with greaseproof paper.•  Remove the puff pastry from the pack and unroll. Sprinkle evenly with the grated cheese reserving about a quarter of it.•  Fold the puff pastry in half and roll back to original size on a floured worktop.•  Using a star pastry cutter cut out as many shapes as you can.•  Transfer your star shapes to a baking tray and brush the tops with milk.•  Sprinkle a little of the remaining cheese on top followed by seasoning of your choice and bake for 10-12 minutes.

Breakfast Tray Bake ✨ #Primark #DIYWhat you need 🥘:•	500g small baby potatoes cubed•	1 x 400g can of baked beans•	100g mushrooms sliced•	A handful of fresh sage leaves (or 1 tsp dried sage)•	8-10 vine tomatoes or 4 large tomatoes halved•	4 eggs•	8 pigs in blankets•	2 tbsp olive oil•	Salt and pepper How to 🧑‍🍳:•	Pre heat oven to 200c and prepare a large oven proof tray•	In a small bowl toss the potatoes in 1 tablespoon of oil and season with salt and pepper spreading out evenly on the tray. •	Transfer to the oven for 20 minutes.•	In the same bowl add the mushrooms second tablespoon of olive oil mushrooms and sage. •	Season stir and add to the tray with the potatoes. •	Add the pigs in blankets and return to the oven for a further 20 minutes.•	Split the can of beans between two oven safe pots then nestle between the other ingredients on the tray. •	Make small wells amongst the ingredients for the eggs and carefully crack them into the wells.•	Return the tray to the oven for a final 10 minutes and prepare your Festive breakfast table!

Come with jo_the_futurist to our #PrimarkCares event 💙 .Primark Cares has nine commitments across three key areas – product planet and people. These commitments range from making all our clothes from recycled or more sustainably sourced materials by 2030 halving carbon emissions across our supply chain over the next seven years and pursuing a living wage for workers in our supply chain. All of the decor for the event was repurposed from other events and included QR codes and information about the programme. The food was sourced locally to minimise the event’s impact and everyone was invited to take home leftovers to minimise food waste. We welcomed influencers and the press to talk about the programme and open up an important conversation about the impact of fashion.

A major throwback of Orlagh and I (henriettarix) on our first trip to NYC together 🍎! It’s crazy to think RIXO was only 2 months old ~ We sold our first dress in September 2015 and this image was (begrudgingly 🤣) taken in November 2015… Orlagh was hungover and in general we don’t take many picture of ourselves! We had no idea what the next 9 years would bring but we knew that we were obsessed with vintage and wanted an international brand that we were in control of. I’m not sure what we’d tell ourselves now if we could go back but RIXO has been all encompassing & we’ve been through it ALL together both personally and professionally growing up through our 20s & 30s building RIXO. Running a fashion business and navigating retail is tough but we’ve met some of the most incredible women along the way. One of those being Phyllis (who’s in the middle of us here) she believed in us before anyone else we met her via IG and have been in touch ever since and bonded over our love of anything old. We used to DM each other from London & NYC and then when we visited we spent a gorgeous day at several museums. Phyliss knew we were starting RIXO up on a shoestring from our uni flat and sent us the most incredible box of vintage accessories that she’d collected over the years that we then used to style all our photoshoots…safe to say she’s our NY fairy godmother! Now 9 years on to have our very first shop in the ground in Soho is a BIG pinch me moment and a dream come true 😆🙏🏼 so we’re taking this moment to reflect and enjoy the journey we’ve been on so far! Thanks to our incredible community on here and all of you we can continue to do what we love & grow RIXO! I’d love to know if anyone else has met someone special via IG… surly it can’t be just us 😊 X

Introducing the July collection 🌞Hi everyone - firstly to say I’m new to doing anything like this on Instagram and not a fan of my voice! (I don’t think anyone is 🙈🤪) but I wanted to really show you the detail and thought that goes into not just the the prints but the cut fit and fabric of each piece we design. I’ve always been obsessed with fit and we’re always trying to improve season after season and really design for how we live our lives. If you haven’t tried rixo before or you have and it’s not suited you this video is definitely worth a watch. From different neck lines (requested by you) to new fabrics we cover everything we think is important when deciding what the perfect piece is for you. Thank you drapersonline! A proud moment for the RIXO TEAM going home with a double win Last Night... Womenswear Brand of the Year and Best Store Design! AND a nomination for Tech Innovator of the year with amazing harperconcierge team who brought TRY BEFORE YOU BUY to life at RIXO!The awards couldnt have come at a more perfect time and we are so proud of our WHOLE team who make RIXO what it is today! When starting any business the Entrepreneurial spirit in you always wants to strive and look for how we can be better but admittedly sometimes we forget to look back appreciate also what we have achieved and where we have come from with no investors to lean on. In such a volatile economic and political landscape its moments like this that keep us resilient always moving forward with our customer in mind but not forgetting to be proud of what weve achieved. Thank you to the whole team again and to our amazing customers and followers who we do it all for! ♥️ Orlagh & Henrietta x

Every single RIXO piece is designed to last a lifetime and deserves to be adorned and women all over the world our #humansofrixo 🌼🤍 We always aim to buy only what we need & never purposefully over produce for sale season however it’s never a crystal ball and sometimes even our limited runs have excess stock ~ so with a challenging economic climate we have decided to enter some of our beautiful current season styles into a sale in the hopes that they can make their way to your home where they belong! Our values haven’t changed and we still believe that sales undermine a pricing strategy that is fair and speaks to the quality of the brand. All our styles are designed in-house with as much love time and care as when Henrietta & Orlagh painted every print in their university living room 🎨We hope you use this sale to treat yourself to something you’ll love and cherish forever ♥️

As we’ve been building out the rixo staples wardrobe we kept going back to what vintage pieces we always styled our rixo with and what we know is hard to find. The perfect cotton blouse that’s reminiscent of a French vintage find was top of the list. Last March in  India we made 3 iteration of blouse until we perfected it. Being there in person and working with the pattern cutter we pinned cut added a peplum changed the neck line multiple times to make something you could wear with our skirts out your favourite jeans all year round. Sold out once we’ll be making sure she’s around for good keeping her in stock in our staples collection so you’ll have her forever like the perfect vintage find.

Want your clothes to go further?We’ve teamed up with VenetiaLaManna recovering fast fashion addict who’s on a mission to slow down her fashion habits and celebrate her existing clothes in a bid to honour the people that made them.Our recent Climate Impact Report shows that buying just one fashion item on Vinted second-hand instead of new saves an average of 1.81 kgCO₂e per item – that’s equivalent to charging your phone 219 times! With lower prices you might even be able to find some higher quality items that can be worn for longer – reducing your impact even further.1 in 5 Vinted members would prefer to buy something second-hand even if it was available for a similar price as new. And that’s why Venetia is selling some of her pre-loved clothes on the app as well as prioritising second-hand purchases. Have a look at her wardrobe VenetiaLaManna and follow her so that she can see what hidden treasures you’re selling… 💎You can read our Climate Impact Report available in the link in our bio.

As it turns out “ugly packaging” (reused packaging) can be better than a new mint-condition box. In fact it reduces the CO2e emissions generated by packaging materials by around 70%. More than half of our members already reuse their boxes and envelopes and this saved more than 17 kilotonnes of CO2 emissions in 2021 - the equivalent of driving to the moon 411 times. So remember: the packaging of your purchases can have a second life too! Second-hand is all about giving a longer life to good items. Almost half of sellers choose to sell their item because it no longer suits their style rather than it being physically worn out. As a buyer second-hand allows you to buy higher quality items for a more affordable price and higher quality means you can wear them longer. To learn more about circularity and Vinted’s community shopping habits have a look at our Sustainability Landing Page (link in bio). #vinted #secondhand #VintedChoices

A single purchase can make a big difference. When you choose to buy a second-hand fashion item on Vinted instead of a new one you save an average of 1.8 kg CO2 - the equivalent of charging your phone 219 times. Imagine the impact this has on an individual level… and multiply it by an international community of 80 million members. We want to keep growing and supporting you so you can make second-hand your first choice. To learn more about avoided emissions open the Climate Impact Report (link in bio). #vinted #secondhand #VintedChoices

The cobbler inside the container. Last July we installed a movable cobbler container in our warehouse located on the outskirts of Paris. There Mustapha and his team fix VEJA sneakers returned by clients with small defects. When a client returns a pair bought on our website or in our stores we don’t throw it away: we fix it. The cobbler team repairs more than 5 500 pairs on average that is 600 pairs per month. All our online orders and logistics for our 4 VEJA stores in Europe go through this location. The people who work at Log’ins have slight disabilities and follow a reintegration program. Now we have this cobbler place where they can be trained in logistics and traditional cobbler’s craft.  In this second episode Daniel Manager of the Repairing and Recycling project at VEJA will guide you through this unique cobbler place. #veja

In 2010 Sébastien & Ghislain — the founders of VEJA — created the concept store centre_commercial.It welcomes projects and brands with transparent sourcing.At the beginning of the project everybody told them it was going to be difficult that this kind of store was complicated. 13 years later it is a 25 people team and one of the best stores of Paris. They launched many projects many new brands many books. Centre Commercial is a catapult for new consistant projects.It is located on Rue de Marseille near Canal Saint-Martin and Place de la République an up-and-coming part of Paris’ 10th district.Find a great selection of VEJAs styles.📸: antoinehuot#veja #centrecommercial

In 2004 VEJA stepped for the first time into the Amazon rainforest the only place in the world where rubber grows wild.Last November a VEJA team from France US and Brazil embarked on a journey into Amazonia to experience the reality of the local rubber producers. We have been working with them for the past 18 years since the VEJA Project started. We started with 20 rubber producers who grew step by step with us. 18 years later more than 1200 local rubber families and 22 associations are working with us. The rubber producers VEJA works with are paid 5 times more than the market price.#veja #vejaproject
